So what do requests look like? I've had a broad range of responses. Sometimes it's simply "I have read your query and would like more. Please send (full/partial) in word doc" 
The best is when they gush about your voice, premise, how well-crafted your opening chapter was, etc.

When I do get a personalized rejection on my query, it's easy to tell. They name my character, my comps are discussed, my premise, etc in detail. They still have aspects of the form attached to it, like the subjectivity line, but it clearly discusses what I sent them.

A form saves an agent time and is usually a polite step aside. Some are short, some are long, but they usually have the following: 

Thank you for your query/opportunity to consider your work. 

Sometimes they throw in your book's title as well. 

and then...

What's the norm for query rejections and requests? I'm so glad you asked. A thread:

Let's start with rejections on queries. You either get a form or a personalized rejection, and they can be hard to differentiate from when you're clinging to any feedback. So let's üëÄat forms

6‚É£ - UPDATE

If you need to modify data in your database, the UPDATE query is what you'll use.

You can update one or more columns in a table based on a condition specified in the WHERE clause. https://t.co/Sc8jP0953o

4‚É£ - GROUP BY

GROUP BY is a useful SQL query that lets you group data based on one or more columns.

You can then use aggregate functions like COUNT, SUM, and AVG to perform calculations on the grouped data https://t.co/oFLB3TVZ0h

3‚É£ - JOIN

JOIN is another essential SQL query that allows you to combine data from multiple tables based on a related column.

There are several types of JOIN, including INNER JOIN, LEFT JOIN, and RIGHT JOIN. https://t.co/dlTRMRRFvT

2‚É£ - WHERE

Another important query is the WHERE clause, which lets you filter data based on specific conditions.

For example, you could use WHERE age > 18 to only retrieve data for people over the age of 18. https://t.co/A3Grkf5Hkb

1‚É£ - SELECT

the SELECT statement is the most basic SQL query and allows you to retrieve data from one or more tables.

For example:
If the Age is in column 4 & the Gender is in column 5, we can sort the data by Age in descending order and by Gender in descending order using the following query üëá

The result will show all employee demographics data, sorted by Age and Gender in descending order. https://t.co/GLadnfmixh
If we have a large number of columns in our dataset and we only want to sort a few of them, we can simplify the query by using column numbers instead of column names in the ORDER BY clause.

The ORDER BY clause can also be used to sort data based on multiple columns. 

For example: 
If we want to sort the data by descending Age and gender, we can use the following queryüëá https://t.co/fn7Y4nNoEM

If we want to count our data more specifically, such as how many males and females are aged over 31, we can use the following query üëá

It will show us that there is one female and three males who are over 31 years old. https://t.co/66QrfDv196

GROUP BY also allows us to group our data based on multiple conditions. 

For example: 
If we want to count Gender and group it by Age and Gender, we can use the following query, which will show us the number of males and females in each age group. https://t.co/hk49gzUaax

If we run the query with DISTINCT(Gender) and GROUP BY Gender, we will get the same result, which is "Male" and "Female". 

This is because there are only two unique values in the Gender column, and both queries group the data based on Gender. https://t.co/AlwpHLfNv0
